    <h2>2.2.7 Properties of metals and alloys</h2>
    <p>
        - As metals are giant structures with strong bonding, they have high melting and boiling points.<br>
        - In pure metals, atoms are arranged in layers, which allows metals to be bent and shaped.<br>
        - Pure metals are too soft for many uses and so are mixed with other metals to make alloys which are harder.<br>
        - The atoms cannot slide over each other as easily as they are different sizes, so the 
        alloys are therefore harder, more resistant to corrosion, and less affected by extreme temperatures.
    </p>
    <h2>2.2.8 Metals as conductors</h2>
    <p>
        - Metals are good conductors of electricity because they have a high number of free (delocalised) electrons, 
        which carry electric charge through the metal.<br>
        - Metals are good conductors of thermal energy for the same reason.<br>
        - Delocalised electrons are electrons that do not belong to any specific metal atom. The particles that make up
        the metal's giant structure are then not atoms but positively charged ions.
    </p>
